A stingray is a flat-bodied fish that belongs to the family of Dasyatidae. 
It has a distinct diamond shape with a long, pointed snout and broad fins that extend from its body. 
Its skin has a rough, sandpaper-like texture and it is usually a brown or gray color. 
Stingrays are known for their sharp, stinging barbs that can be found near the base of their tails. 
They use these barbs as a defense mechanism against predators. 
Stingrays are found in warm ocean waters all around the world, but are commonly found in the tropics. 
They are often seen swimming along the ocean floor, preying on small fish and crustaceans.
